title: For Sale/Trade:  Kel-Tec Sub2000 - Glock model 9mm - Sub 2000
postcontent:
Up for trade is a brand new, unfired Kel-tec Sub2000, Glock mag version in 9mm with box, papers, 1 mag, and factory accessories.  

These were hard to find before the frenzy, almost impossible to locate now.  I paid over retail obviously, so please don't waste your time with subpar cash offers as I will not bother to respond - am not in need to sell and will keep it or take to auction if need be.  

I put the trade value around $850.  I know that seems high, but it appears everyone has jacked up the value of their stuff, and as such, I cannot be exptected to take all the loss.

I don't like it either and hope it will be over soon and return to normal, but none of us really know.  When you see $700 ARs and AKs going for $1500-$2200+, and $13 mags going for $50, one has no choice to adjust their prices accordingly (thanks Libs and american sheeple!) or stay out of the game entirely.  

With the exception of revolvers, shotguns, and semi-autos under 10 rds, everything is high now.

Prefer FTF and all trades must be FTF so we can both inspect each other's items, but will ship for $40 from FFL to FFL for the right price.  

I am looking for a these in trade (combinations work too), or trade plus cash.  I can also kick in cash or other stuff for higher-end items:

.45 or 9mm autos (no 1911's please) - am partial to Glocks/sigs/HK.

.22 pistol (Ruger MK or similiar), Keltec PMR.

Modern revolvers (LCR, GP100, etc), don't need safe queen collectibles or Grandpa's 50 year keepsake, sorry.

Semi-auto battle rifles (5.56, .308, AKs, Saiga) 

Tactical shotguns, pump or semi-auto with 18" barrels (590A1, 870, Benelli)

Glock 4th gen mags or 9mm ammo (124 or 147gr) - no 115gr unless its on the super cheap and no steel/aluminum case at all.

Am open to other trades not listed as long as its not junk (hipoint, taurus, DPMS, etc.) - worse I can say is no thanks.  

Absolutely no bolt-action rifles, long-barreled or O/U shotguns, or any other FUDD style hunting weapons please.  If there is wood on it or it's camo, I basically have no interest in it.

Again, trade is king, thanks for looking.

title: Want To Buy:  Free Market
postcontent:
Over the past few days I have noticed various adds consisting of complaints over the recent price spikes in firearms and calling it 'gouging'. 

I was under the impression that we gun folk were freedom loving, Constitution abiding, advocates of the FREE MARKET. But apparently some people don't see it that way. 

Charging high prices for certian guns or ammo is not 'evil', as some socialists would have you believe, but rather a natrual by-product of the AMERICAN Capitalist free market system.

The free market is made up of two fundamental factors which dictate price. Supply and demand. When demand rises but supply remains constant, prices increase. Likewise when demand decreases, prices along with supply will decrease with it and thus the markets constantly strive for a point where supply = demand. This point is called equilibrium.

 With talk of legislation and bans around the corner, people are suddenly in a frenzy to buy firearms and ammunition. This is the demand. Thus prices will natrually increase to reflect demand until supply is increased. 

This is not 'evil' because in a free market you are free to buy or sell anything you want. You aren't forced to buy anything! If the price is too high, you will not buy. If you feel you can sell a box of .22 for one million dollars you are free to do so. But nobody will buy it. And you will either decrease your price or never sell it. You see this system isn't evil because you aren't being forced to buy anything. Boycotting isn't neccessary because the price you are willing to pay decides the price. If you feel something is priced to high don't buy it! And by doing so you are decreasing demand which will in turn help the market stabalize and reach equilibrium. 

Lets not embarass ourselves to the socialists in Washington who would want to regulate small buisnesses and the American free market out of work. Unless you want some federal law dictating how and what you can sell and at what prices.
